text: I just returned from seeing this movie and I was very impressed! Great movie with a good balance of emotional content and great timing on the comedy. Here's a copy/paste from my fb review. I would highly recommend this movie to young and "old" alike:)  The Intern, starring Robert Deniro. Great movie!! I highly recommend it. A light hearted comedy that was well done! Robert Deniro plays a retired CEO of a once bustling phone book company, now no longer in business due to the high tech computer era. He quickly realizes he's had enough of playing shuffle board and other retirement activities, and that he misses the challenges and the focus of the working world. So he decides to answer an add for a new upstart fashion company looking to hire senior interns to gain more "old school" business perspective. He soon learns that while he may be considered "washed up" by the much younger employees of this new company..he still has a few tricks up his well pressed sleeve and quickly garners both the admiration and respect of his younger co-workers. The owner of the company played by Ann Hathaway, however, proves to be a much larger but rewarding challenge to the retired CEO.

text: This film is a fun, sweet movie that is really asking the question, "Why are men of this generation weaker than the last generation?" The problem isn't the men of today. The problem is Nostalgia. The women of this generation are looking at the men of the past with rose tinted glasses. We forgot the struggle women went through to get where we are now. text: This would have been much better if it didn't have those horrible *neo-feminist* undertones. Nobody minds a strong female lead. It's also good to see both strong female and male leads play opposite one another with good screen chemistry. But when you get into the whole, "He was sexist" and "They can't take me because I'm a strong working woman"  it just taints the whole movie with a stink that permeates social media and pop culture today.   I'd like to make the distinction between feminism - a movement for equal rights among men and women - and neo-feminism, a plague that paints almost all men as sexist pigs and petitions for inequality among the sexes with bitterness and hate.  Otherwise, pretty good movie.

text: The question she says at the end, "How have men gone from Jack Nicholson and Harrison Ford to -looks at dorky men-". I find really irritating. Western women claim that they like dorky, compassionate, sensitive, some degree of metro-sexuality, humble, nerds and we're bombarded with movies in which a hero that's all that personified, somehow wins the girl. However, lots of studies suggest that women are attracted to very manly, even aggressive/strong, dominant men - it only makes sense from a evolutionary standpoint. So when someone says 'how have men gone this way', the answer is they're aspiring to be attractive to what modern women pretend they like.  I don't know what my point was, I just feel that people seem to hate the current generation of young 20-something men, like we're constantly being told 'oh men have been such bastards for the last century', so when men evolve into these limp, dorky, sensitive guys women look at them in disgust and yearn for some manly men, who they would probably label misogynist if they thought about it for a second. Poor fuckers can't win.

text: The Intern(2015) Movie Review :  I like these kind of movies where you can sit back and relax. I find the emotions in humans bigger and larger than the powers of superheroes. The Intern is about a young CEO Jules played by Anne Hathaway who has given her everything to set up her e-commerce business. She has taken care of it like her child and brought it to a success within a short span. Even her husband supports her along the way by dropping out from his job and looking after their daughter. However in her hectic schedule she is not be able to spend much time with her family. Even to herself. She is missing her life and her habit of taking everything on her shoulders makes her and her company miss all the schedules. This is where her newly appointed senior intern Ben, played by Robert De Niro, shows her the way to lead her life. The bond between Ben and Jules forms the crux of the story. Ben is a 70 year old widower and a very organized old school person who has worked for 40 years in a phonebook printing office. This movie shows a clear distinction between the two generations and their work culture. And surprisingly,  the old generation seemed to have managed their work pretty well. Eventually,  Jules is able to balance her life as Ben becomes her bestfriend. The movie is of today's generation and we can completely relate it to our corporate lives. The bond between Ben and Jules has been showcased very well and both the lead actors played their roles to perfection. I loved the movie. You can watch it on playstore and I am sure it makes for a nice Sunday morning watch.

Her husband sacrificed his career to be a stay at home dad, so she can run her company and live her dream. She only seems interested in him when she figures out he has been cheating on her and worries she will lose him. She doesn‚Äôt want to give up any control in her company even though it is taking her away from her family. She treats DeNiro‚Äôs character like he has the plague just because he is old. People act like her husband is selfish for cheating and disappointment that she takes him back in the end.
